[1]
Date: Mon 10 Jul 2006
From: Joe Dudley <jdudley@eai.com>
Source: RPP Noticias, 6 Jul 2006 [edited]
<http://www.rpp.com.pe/portada/nacional/43411_1.php>

Senasa confirms that 6 people were infected with Anthrax in Lambayeque
-----------------------------------------------
At least 6 people got infected with anthrax after being in close contact
with infected cattle in Monsefu district (northwest Peru) as reported by
SENASA, the Agricultural Ministry.
The chief of SENASA (Esmilda Arevalo) in Lambeyeque said that 6 people were
observed with anthrax signs after a screening in 2 towns in the area. The
outbreak was detected last Friday [30 Jun 2006], after SENASA workers were
warned about cattle dead due to anthrax by residents of Pompape and Villa
Hermosa de Monsefu. Arevalo said that the outbreak is very contagious [sic]
and could be passed to farmers if they don't follow SENASA recommendations
to bury dead animals at 7 meters deep in the ground.
She also stated that SENASA experts have gone to those towns in order to
detect other cases in cattle and that vaccination has started in the
cattle. The director of Animal Health of SENASA, Oscar Rodriguez, indicated
that some producers (farmers) will not vaccinate their animals due to old
beliefs that the animals are pregnant and could die due to the vaccine.
Dominguez exhorted the producers to vaccinate their animals and to notify
SENASA of the existence of anthrax cases or any other contagious disease.
--
