[2]
Date: Mon 10 Jul 2006
From: Joe Dudley <jdudley@eai.com>
Source: Las Gran Epoca, 7 Jul 2006 [edited]
<http://www.lagranepoca.com/news/6-7-7/2900.html>

SENASA reports that at least 6 people were infected with anthrax in Monsefu
district, Lambayeque department (North of Peru) after working with sick
cattle. Arevalo (chief of SENASA in Lambayeque) said that 6 people were
observed with anthrax signs after a screening in 2 towns in the area. The
outbreak was detected last Friday [30 Jun 2006] after SENASA workers were
warned about 12 cattle dead due to anthrax by residents of Pompape and
Villa Hermosa de Monsefu.
Arevalo ... also indicated that SENASA experts have gone to those towns in
order to detect other cases in cattle and that vaccination has started in
the cattle. A resident of Pompape asked the authorities to get more
involved with the affected people that don't show complications. He said
that their neighbors were sick due to working with sick animals. He also
said that they need more attention, because although they are vaccinating,
some animals are still dying. SENASA stated that there are 900 animals in
Pompape and Villa Hermosa and that 830 were vaccinated. The Chief of Animal
Health of SENASA warned that the bacteria causing anthrax could remain for
more than 40 years in the site if not adequately controlled. There are
endemic areas in Peru, where human cases of anthrax in skin are commonly
seen. Since the end of the last decade, there has been a policy of
vaccination of cattle in order to eradicate the disease.
--
Joseph P. Dudley, Ph.D.
Chief Scientist, Biosecurity and Bioinformatics
EAI Corporation
4301 North Fairfax Drive
