Arlington, VA 22203
<jdudley@eai.com>
[Firstly, anthrax is infectious; it is not contagious. Secondly, if at all
possible, carcasses should be burnt, not buried. Traditionally, the advice
was to bury in quicklime, not agricultural lime, but I doubt whether folks
can find that nowadays. And 7 meters strikes me as a gross typo error for 2
meters. If the carcass has not been opened, decomposition results in a
rapid drop in pH, and this is lethal to the vegetative cells. But if the
animal has been necropsied or opened up by scavengers, there will be
extensive sporulation. Burying such a carcass just ensures problems on
another day, thus the advice to burn.
Yet again, we are seeing cattle deaths immediately post-vaccination. If one
can, whenever there is a suspicion that some animals might be incubating
disease, it is best to treat them 1st with long-acting antibiotics, and
then vaccinate them 7-10 days later.
Bovine anthrax is reported annually in Peru and occurs in about 5 out of 10
of the coastal departments. Lately, it has been reported in the following
departments: Ancash, Cajamarca, Huanuco, Ica, La Libertad, Lima, Moquegua,
and Tumbes. The high frequency of human cutaneous cases indicates that it
is extensively underreported. To find Lambayeque, go to:
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/peru_pol91.jpg>.
- Mod.MHJ]
